==== ENTRY 1 ====
HEADWORD: Sepal
<hw>Se"pal</hw> <pr>(?)</pr>, <pos>n.</pos> <ety>[NL.
<ets>sepalum</ets>, formed in imitation of NL. <ets>petalum</ets>,
petal, to denote one of the divisions of the calyx: cf. F.
<ets>s⟦eacute⟧pale</ets>.]</ety> <fld>(Bot.)</fld> <def>A leaf or
division of the calyx.</def>⟦br⟧
[<source>1913 Webster</source>]</p>

<p><note>⟦hand⟧ When the calyx consists of but one part, it is said to
be <xex>monosepalous</xex>; when of two parts, it is said to be
<xex>disepalous</xex>; when of a variable and indefinite number of
parts, it is said to be <xex>polysepalous</xex>; when of several parts
united, it is properly called <xex>gamosepalous</xex>.</note>⟦br⟧
[<source>1913 Webster</source>]</p>

<p><-- p. 1312 --></p>

<p><ent>Sepaled</ent>⟦br⟧
